WEBVTT

1
00:00:47.260 --> 00:00:51.059
Inspired by events
in Astrid Lindgren's life


2
00:01:19.060 --> 00:01:22.739
Happy birthday Astrid

3
00:01:44.940 --> 00:01:48.659
Happy birthday Astrid
from Class 4A


4
00:02:22.740 --> 00:02:25.099
Dear Astrid Lindgren..

5
00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:28.859
We're a 4th-year class
from Hästhult School.


6
00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:32.339
We want to wish you
a happy birthday-


7
00:02:32.540 --> 00:02:35.739
- and thank you for all your stories..

8
00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:40.259
Ingvar gets the first turn.
(Go on, read it!)


9
00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:42.059
Hi Astrid!

10
00:02:42.220 --> 00:02:46.459
My mum and dad have read
your books to me since 1 was little.


11
00:02:46.660 --> 00:02:51.139
I wonder: How can you write so well
about being a child-


12
00:02:51.340 --> 00:02:54.379
- when you haven't been one
for so long?


13
00:02:56.420 --> 00:03:00.779
BECOMING ASTRID

14
00:03:02.300 --> 00:03:06.899
"I have chosen him, so that he will
direct his children and his household-


15
00:03:07.060 --> 00:03:14.219
"- to keep the way of the Lord
by doing what is right and just.


16
00:03:14.380 --> 00:03:18.819
"Thus the Lord will bring about
his promise to Abraham.


17
00:03:18.980 --> 00:03:20.859
"The Lord said:

18
00:03:21.060 --> 00:03:26.219
"The outcry against Sodom
and Gomorrah is so great-


19
00:03:26.420 --> 00:03:30.659
"- and their sin so grievous-

20
00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:34.059
"- that I will go down and see-

21
00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:40.139
"- if what they have done is as bad
as the outcry that has reached me.


22
00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:46.859
"The men turned away
and went toward Sodom.


23
00:03:48.780 --> 00:03:52.579
"But Abraham remained
standing before the Lord.


24
00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:59.139
"Then Abraham
turned to the Lord and said:


25
00:04:01.580 --> 00:04:06.179
"Will you sweep away the righteous...

26
00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:11.659
"... with the wicked?"

27
00:04:18.460 --> 00:04:23.059
Where would you rather live,
Sodom or Gomorrah?


28
00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:25.059
Neither!

29
00:04:25.220 --> 00:04:27.579
In Gomorrah
they only say good morning.


30
00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:31.579
And in Sodom they drink
soda for all eternity.


31
00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:33.859
Thank you, Astrid, that's enough.

32
00:04:34.980 --> 00:04:39.219
It's true!
Good morning. Soda.


33
00:04:39.380 --> 00:04:44.379
- Good morning, soda.
- The next blasphemer is walking home!


34
00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:08.859
May I?

35
00:05:20.140 --> 00:05:22.099
You're so pretty.

36
00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:24.979
If I were a man,
I'd fall in love with you.


37
00:05:25.140 --> 00:05:30.019
I'd see that crazy mind of yours
and fall in love right away.


38
00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:33.059
May I?

39
00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:10.139
Let's dance.

40
00:06:10.300 --> 00:06:13.899
- I don't think so.
- Yes, let's dance, Berta!


41
00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:33.739
Your father is here.

42
00:06:56.100 --> 00:06:58.939
Nice, sis!

43
00:07:06.100 --> 00:07:08.059
Come on, Gunnar.

44
00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:25.179
Oh, I...
I just have to scream.


45
00:07:27.060 --> 00:07:31.539
Good morning! Soda!

46
00:07:32.860 --> 00:07:36.819
Good morning, soda!

47
00:07:38.220 --> 00:07:42.099
Good morning, soda!

48
00:07:46.340 --> 00:07:49.619
- Good morning!
- Soda!


49
00:08:03.140 --> 00:08:05.979
Astrid?

50
00:08:06.140 --> 00:08:08.819
You're over an hour late.

51
00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:12.299
What were you thinking?

52
00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:16.339
- I came home with Gunnar.
- She did.


53
00:08:16.580 --> 00:08:20.939
Gunnar can stay out until 10.
You have to be home at 9.


54
00:08:21.100 --> 00:08:23.979
Why is he allowed to stay out later?

55
00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:27.819
Gunnar is a boy and you're a girl.

56
00:08:27.980 --> 00:08:32.819
- But you say we're all equal before God.
- Don't bring our Lord into this!


57
00:08:33.020 --> 00:08:37.699
- You always bring God into everything!
- You'll wake the whole house!


58
00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:41.859
- But if we're all equal before God...
- Astrid...


59
00:08:42.060 --> 00:08:45.779
- ... then there should be no difference.
- Good night.


60
00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:49.699
You're only 16...
Settle down.


61
00:09:38.580 --> 00:09:40.899
Astrid, get started in the stable.

62
00:09:56.660 --> 00:09:58.939
Let's warm ourselves.

63
00:10:47.060 --> 00:10:51.579
In Jesus' name we gather here
Bless this food, oh Jesus dear


64
00:10:51.780 --> 00:10:57.699
And hold in Your protective hand
our home, our king, our fatherland


65
00:10:57.860 --> 00:10:59.579
Amen.

66
00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:16.579
I saw Reinhold Blomberg today.

67
00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:23.139
The "Vimmerby Times" comes out twice
a week now, and he needs an assistant.


68
00:11:23.300 --> 00:11:27.219
- Tell the story about Old Ham.
- Not that again!


69
00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:32.979
- Please, Astrid!
- I've told it a thousand times.


70
00:11:33.140 --> 00:11:36.579
The editor remembered
your essay that was published.


71
00:11:36.780 --> 00:11:42.179
"Life on Our Farm". Written by
Astrid Ericsson, our own Selma Lagerlöf.


72
00:11:42.340 --> 00:11:45.699
- You don't even know who that is!
- Bless that man.


73
00:11:45.860 --> 00:11:49.499
Blomberg was left alone
with seven children when his wife died.


74
00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:54.819
Berta says his new wife is crazy.
But now they're getting divorced.


75
00:11:54.980 --> 00:11:59.219
- We don't gossip while we eat.
- Good thing there's time between meals.


76
00:11:59.380 --> 00:12:02.379
As I said, I saw Blomberg.

77
00:12:03.460 --> 00:12:08.099
And he's looking for an intern.
He'd like to meet you, Astrid.


78
00:12:08.260 --> 00:12:10.499
I'm sorry?

79
00:12:13.580 --> 00:12:18.539
- You'll still have to do your chores.
- Blomberg wants to meet me?


80
00:12:26.580 --> 00:12:29.139
Tell him I'll be there.

81
00:12:53.420 --> 00:12:56.059
VIMMERBY TIMES

82
00:13:26.940 --> 00:13:28.419
Hello, Ĺke!

83
00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:34.779
I'm here to see your father.
Is he at home?


84
00:13:34.980 --> 00:13:37.819
He's working.

85
00:13:37.980 --> 00:13:42.219
Yes, but I don't understand a word.
The woman is completely mad!


86
00:13:44.660 --> 00:13:47.139
Come in.

87
00:13:49.060 --> 00:13:52.259
How should I know?

88
00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:58.179
You'll just have to tell her...
Yes, I understand.


89
00:13:58.380 --> 00:14:03.499
I have to go now. I've got an
impatient little intern waiting for me.


90
00:14:04.740 --> 00:14:07.099
Fine. Let's do that.

91
00:14:15.300 --> 00:14:17.899
Newspaper.

92
00:14:19.380 --> 00:14:22.859
Yes. I'm good at spelling...

93
00:14:23.900 --> 00:14:26.619
I'm a hard worker...

94
00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:32.019
And I'm happy to work overtime
if you need me to.


95
00:14:33.060 --> 00:14:35.739
Newspaper.

96
00:14:37.340 --> 00:14:40.419
Yes, newspapers are important.

97
00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:45.459
I always read the newspaper
when my father is finished with it.


98
00:14:47.100 --> 00:14:49.739
I say: Newspaper.

99
00:14:54.500 --> 00:14:56.659
Newspaper...?

100
00:15:01.860 --> 00:15:05.859
- Typewriter?
- Printer's ink.


101
00:15:08.540 --> 00:15:11.019
- Paper?
- News.


102
00:15:14.260 --> 00:15:16.299
Light.

103
00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:20.299
Future.

104
00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:22.619
Freedom.

105
00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:25.939
Yes!

106
00:15:26.140 --> 00:15:29.299
First write up the obituaries.

107
00:15:29.460 --> 00:15:32.179
Then the birthdays, weddings,
silver anniversaries...


108
00:15:32.340 --> 00:15:35.939
- Father?
- We're working.


109
00:15:36.100 --> 00:15:38.939
And then proof-read these.

110
00:15:40.860 --> 00:15:44.099
Olivia is here. She's crying.

111
00:15:45.860 --> 00:15:50.379
- Bloody hell...
- Proof-read...


112
00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:59.579
- I need you to sign the papers.
- Why are you coming here now?


113
00:15:59.740 --> 00:16:02.899
- Can you just sign them?
- Oh, please...


114
00:16:03.060 --> 00:16:06.939
- Reinhold...
- I'll never sign them. You know that.


115
00:16:09.340 --> 00:16:12.699
You got the job! 
Congratulations!

116
00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:20.059
Really, Berta...

117
00:16:21.420 --> 00:16:24.659
- That's a typewriter...!
- Well, type then!


118
00:16:24.860 --> 00:16:27.059
I don't know if I can!

119
00:17:08.300 --> 00:17:12.299
Hi, Astrid. My name is Lisa.
I write stories, too.


120
00:17:13.300 --> 00:17:16.539
I don't spell very well,
but I don't care.


121
00:17:16.740 --> 00:17:21.139
When I write, it's as if
everything else disappears.


122
00:17:21.340 --> 00:17:24.339
But in a good way.
I'm alone with my thoughts.


123
00:17:24.580 --> 00:17:28.299
I feel free.
Maybe it's the same for you?


124
00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:42.619
I also wrote in
all the special birthdays.


125
00:17:42.820 --> 00:17:46.659
And the obituaries. 
Every one of them.

126
00:17:48.420 --> 00:17:53.859
Yesterday I wrote about some boys
who hoisted their friend up a flagpole.


127
00:17:54.060 --> 00:17:57.939
And I wrote a story
about a pregnant girl...


128
00:17:58.100 --> 00:18:02.699
- She nearly died from eating matches.
Matches?!


129
00:18:02.860 --> 00:18:06.779
- She ate matches?
- She was pregnant.


130
00:18:06.940 --> 00:18:10.739
She'd heard that the phosphorus
in the matches would kill the baby.


131
00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:14.659
- But nothing happened to the baby.
- That's enough, Astrid.


132
00:18:17.020 --> 00:18:19.979
And I proof-read
all of Blomberg's articles.


133
00:18:20.140 --> 00:18:24.939
Like I said.
Vimmerby's own Selma Lagerlöf.


134
00:18:25.100 --> 00:18:28.219
Astrid Ericsson's
wonderful journey through Sweden.


135
00:18:28.380 --> 00:18:30.579
Enough!

136
00:18:48.340 --> 00:18:50.659
Don't play with your food!

137
00:18:50.820 --> 00:18:52.099
That's enough.

138
00:18:52.300 --> 00:18:54.899
- Throw harder!
- No more throwing.


139
00:18:57.260 --> 00:18:58.899
No throwing!

140
00:19:03.500 --> 00:19:06.059
It's raining potatoes!

141
00:19:30.860 --> 00:19:32.339
Hello.

142
00:19:33.820 --> 00:19:35.979
The editor will be back soon.

143
00:19:41.220 --> 00:19:44.419
Would you like to sit down and wait?

144
00:19:54.380 --> 00:19:56.859
I've come for my silverware.

145
00:19:57.060 --> 00:20:00.099
- Not this again, Olivia.
- I really want my silverware.


146
00:20:00.220 --> 00:20:04.859
- I don't have it.
- Let go of me!


147
00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:08.499
- Shame on you! Shame!
- Get out! Out!


148
00:20:08.700 --> 00:20:11.179
Let go of me! Ouch!

149
00:20:20.500 --> 00:20:25.299
Let's go and cheer ourselves up
with some coffee and cake.


150
00:20:54.420 --> 00:20:57.699
We lost our child, our baby.

151
00:21:00.700 --> 00:21:02.659
A little girl.

152
00:21:07.900 --> 00:21:11.739
There is no greater grief for a woman
than to lose a child.


153
00:21:16.980 --> 00:21:20.099
Or for a man, I suppose?

154
00:21:28.060 --> 00:21:30.699
You have...

155
00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:34.179
- What was it?
- Ink.


156
00:21:50.900 --> 00:21:53.499
Here...

157
00:21:53.660 --> 00:21:58.059
I think this is something that
might interest our female readers.


158
00:22:01.780 --> 00:22:05.739
And that one there might interest
our male readers.


159
00:22:11.060 --> 00:22:12.499
Blomberg.

160
00:22:15.740 --> 00:22:17.939
No, I'd forgotten!

161
00:22:19.300 --> 00:22:21.379
Now?!

162
00:22:23.100 --> 00:22:25.539
Right... I'm on my way.

163
00:22:27.700 --> 00:22:30.939
You take the opening
of the new railroad.


164
00:22:32.140 --> 00:22:35.699
- Me?
- Yes, write up a report.


165
00:23:09.860 --> 00:23:14.859
In America the trains
famously rush by-


166
00:23:15.060 --> 00:23:17.099
- at such tremendous speeds-

167
00:23:17.260 --> 00:23:23.379
- that day and night fly past
in a blur of black and white streaks.


168
00:23:26.940 --> 00:23:29.139
But not this train..

169
00:23:29.300 --> 00:23:32.859
It rolled along
at just the right pace-


170
00:23:33.060 --> 00:23:37.059
- for us all to delight in the
beautiful countryside of Smĺland.


171
00:23:39.420 --> 00:23:45.579
From time to time we would arrive
at a little red station house-


172
00:23:45.740 --> 00:23:50.419
- with endless streams of bunting
and decorations...


173
00:23:52.140 --> 00:23:56.299
where crowds of people
had gathered to watch...


174
00:23:57.620 --> 00:23:59.419
...and wave.

175
00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:02.259
You really can write.

176
00:24:06.780 --> 00:24:09.139
You're a star.

177
00:24:12.780 --> 00:24:15.579
Shine a little on me.

178
00:24:16.660 --> 00:24:18.819
I need it

179
00:24:33.220 --> 00:24:37.379
Like her. That's how
I want my hair. Just like this.


180
00:25:03.900 --> 00:25:06.099
Do it.

181
00:26:48.940 --> 00:26:51.259
I have a new hairstyle.

182
00:26:53.980 --> 00:26:56.139
I'll say!

183
00:26:56.300 --> 00:27:01.339
My mother thinks this haircut
is a one-way ticket to hell.


184
00:27:02.740 --> 00:27:07.139
I think God has more important concerns
than a pretty secretary's hair.


185
00:27:13.260 --> 00:27:15.779
I'll be at the print shop.

186
00:27:44.100 --> 00:27:46.739
Why aren't you asleep?

187
00:27:52.980 --> 00:27:54.739
- Goodnight.
- Goodnight.


188
00:28:06.060 --> 00:28:08.179
Yes, I see.

189
00:28:10.300 --> 00:28:12.059
Yes.

190
00:28:15.300 --> 00:28:17.419
Yes, I understand.

191
00:28:34.100 --> 00:28:36.459
Is something wrong?

192
00:29:23.220 --> 00:29:25.779
This is not a good idea.

193
00:29:29.100 --> 00:29:31.699
You should go home now.

194
00:31:13.940 --> 00:31:16.779
Shall we dance?

195
00:31:16.940 --> 00:31:19.939
No, I think I'll go home.

196
00:31:36.580 --> 00:31:38.739
The proof-reading?

197
00:31:39.980 --> 00:31:44.099
- Done.
- The adverts?


198
00:31:48.420 --> 00:31:51.779
- They're right there.
- Right...


199
00:31:59.300 --> 00:32:01.899
And my bedroom?

200
00:32:45.060 --> 00:32:48.979
Newspaper.
I say "newspaper...


201
00:32:50.580 --> 00:32:55.499
- "Vimmerby Times".
- Talented young female journalist.


202
00:34:14.140 --> 00:34:16.219
Astrid?

203
00:34:19.420 --> 00:34:22.419
We're all tired.
But we just have to push on.


204
00:34:24.620 --> 00:34:28.379
The smoke is making me sick.

205
00:34:35.820 --> 00:34:38.339
What's wrong?

206
00:34:39.740 --> 00:34:42.819
Is it that time of the month?

207
00:34:46.060 --> 00:34:48.899
Go home and lie down for a while.

208
00:35:30.260 --> 00:35:32.819
It's quiet here today.

209
00:35:38.740 --> 00:35:41.099
Hey...

210
00:35:42.300 --> 00:35:44.619
What is it?

211
00:35:52.100 --> 00:35:54.099
My period hasn't come.

212
00:35:57.180 --> 00:35:59.659
How long ago was it?

213
00:36:01.540 --> 00:36:04.339
You promised me you'd be careful!

214
00:36:12.220 --> 00:36:14.579
I won't leave you.

215
00:36:20.260 --> 00:36:22.619
Are your breasts sore?

216
00:36:25.940 --> 00:36:28.259
And you're tired?

217
00:36:31.340 --> 00:36:33.979
Do you feel sick?

218
00:36:35.500 --> 00:36:38.299
Not so much anymore.

219
00:36:41.820 --> 00:36:44.619
Take off your dress.

220
00:36:55.860 --> 00:36:58.659
And your petticoat.

221
00:37:07.900 --> 00:37:09.979
Astrid...

222
00:37:11.580 --> 00:37:16.419
We live next to the vicar.
Your father is the churchwarden.


223
00:37:16.660 --> 00:37:19.019
- We live off the bounty of church land.
- Yes.


224
00:37:19.220 --> 00:37:22.379
- No one must find out!
- No.


225
00:37:22.620 --> 00:37:25.819
- Don't say a word to anyone.
- No.


226
00:37:25.980 --> 00:37:28.739
Is that understood?

227
00:37:29.420 --> 00:37:31.299
Put your clothes on.

228
00:37:52.660 --> 00:37:55.339
Go to your room.

229
00:38:14.700 --> 00:38:17.219
My deepest apologies.

230
00:38:21.980 --> 00:38:26.339
I have no excuse for this.
I take full responsibility.


231
00:38:29.980 --> 00:38:33.739
My situation is unfortunately
rather complicated.


232
00:38:33.940 --> 00:38:37.099
I'm still only separated from Olivia,
and she's taken me to court.


233
00:38:37.260 --> 00:38:42.219
But when my divorce is settled,
everything will be much easier.


234
00:38:42.380 --> 00:38:44.139
Easier?

235
00:38:44.260 --> 00:38:49.059
I've found a clinic where Astrid
can have the baby in full discretion.


236
00:38:49.220 --> 00:38:52.299
I assure you of my good intentions..

237
00:38:53.700 --> 00:38:58.379
We could pledge ourselves to each
other now, discreetly of course.


238
00:39:02.500 --> 00:39:05.619
As long as the parents are pledged
to each other, the child is legitimate.


239
00:39:05.740 --> 00:39:11.219
- The child will bear my name.
- We know very well What a pledge means.


240
00:39:12.620 --> 00:39:14.779
She's dazzling.

241
00:39:16.580 --> 00:39:20.939
She's truly gifted.
Full of life and energy.


242
00:39:22.900 --> 00:39:25.099
I love Astrid.

243
00:40:05.380 --> 00:40:07.299
It went well.

244
00:40:12.820 --> 00:40:18.139
I need to leave town.
I can't stay. What...


245
00:40:19.260 --> 00:40:22.939
What will I do
when my stomach starts growing?


246
00:40:23.100 --> 00:40:26.219
I won't be able
to show myself anywhere.


247
00:40:29.340 --> 00:40:32.739
- You have to help me.
- You can go to Stockholm.


248
00:40:32.940 --> 00:40:36.779
Take that secretarial course
we've talked about.


249
00:40:40.300 --> 00:40:42.339
Hey...

250
00:41:08.220 --> 00:41:12.419
This is from Mother.
Some bread, cheese and sausage.


251
00:41:28.340 --> 00:41:30.699
You can do this.

252
00:42:25.380 --> 00:42:28.259
Dear Astrid. My name is Jenny..

253
00:42:29.420 --> 00:42:31.859
You write a lot about death..

254
00:42:32.100 --> 00:42:37.059
There are lots of dead people
in your stories. Pippi's mother...


255
00:42:37.220 --> 00:42:40.499
Jonathan dies, Karl dies..

256
00:42:41.740 --> 00:42:44.419
Mio's mother is gone, too..

257
00:42:44.580 --> 00:42:49.139
But when I read about it
in your books, I just want to live.


258
00:42:49.300 --> 00:42:52.259
You just want to live..

259
00:42:55.780 --> 00:42:59.819
Stenography is a secretary's
most important tool.


260
00:42:59.980 --> 00:43:02.459
It's much faster than...

261
00:43:52.220 --> 00:43:53.779
- Hello.
- Hello.


262
00:43:53.940 --> 00:43:56.499
- Hello, Astrid!
- Hello, Anna.


263
00:44:00.380 --> 00:44:02.979
- Hello.
- Hello.


264
00:44:09.940 --> 00:44:14.219
- Isn't it cold enough in here already?
- She's cooking fish again.


265
00:44:14.340 --> 00:44:17.179
Astrid, we're out of firewood.

266
00:44:25.060 --> 00:44:28.219
Look, I made you a hat.

267
00:44:28.420 --> 00:44:30.659
Anna's having a party.

268
00:44:30.820 --> 00:44:34.699
- She has firewood and a gramophone.
- Saga...


269
00:44:45.220 --> 00:44:48.219
- What is it?
- I'm tired.


270
00:45:13.380 --> 00:45:15.859
"The Road to Freedom".

271
00:45:16.060 --> 00:45:19.579
That woman on the front page,
Eva Andén, is a lawyer.


272
00:45:19.740 --> 00:45:22.259
- A female lawyer?
- Yes.


273
00:45:23.700 --> 00:45:25.939
She helps pregnant women.

274
00:45:26.980 --> 00:45:29.499
Anna had hers in Copenhagen.

275
00:45:29.660 --> 00:45:33.699
Eva Andén found her a foster family.
She helps everybody.


276
00:45:35.580 --> 00:45:39.339
- Where's the baby now?
- I don't know.


277
00:45:42.260 --> 00:45:45.899
- She doesn't know where her baby is?
- Get the door!


278
00:45:46.100 --> 00:45:51.179
- Telegram for Ericsson.
- Ericsson.


279
00:46:00.100 --> 00:46:04.539
"Astrid, phone me.
I must see you. Yours. "


280
00:46:06.780 --> 00:46:09.219
I think my fiancé misses me.

281
00:46:28.100 --> 00:46:30.259
Hello.

282
00:46:30.460 --> 00:46:35.499
My husband is expecting me.
Gustafsson. Axel Gustafsson.


283
00:46:35.700 --> 00:46:39.819
Your husband is in room 218.
First floor.


284
00:47:27.420 --> 00:47:29.459
Aren't you feeling well?

285
00:47:31.100 --> 00:47:32.979
It's a bloody circus here.

286
00:47:35.060 --> 00:47:37.419
Olivia has heard rumours.

287
00:47:38.620 --> 00:47:41.339
She wants me locked up.

288
00:47:41.540 --> 00:47:45.299
- What do you mean?
- Adultery.


289
00:47:45.500 --> 00:47:48.819
I could go to prison.

290
00:47:50.460 --> 00:47:52.779
Prison?

291
00:47:53.940 --> 00:47:57.299
She's had the court
postpone the divorce.


292
00:47:57.500 --> 00:48:00.739
She wants to prove
that I got you pregnant.


293
00:48:01.820 --> 00:48:06.579
Wherever you have the baby,
you must give the father's name.


294
00:48:06.740 --> 00:48:10.379
They just have to look in
the church records: Reinhold Blomberg.


295
00:48:10.580 --> 00:48:12.859
They'll have their proof.

296
00:48:14.020 --> 00:48:16.859
What will I tell my children?

297
00:48:20.420 --> 00:48:22.379
No mother...

298
00:48:25.220 --> 00:48:27.539
and their father in prison.

299
00:48:30.420 --> 00:48:32.659
Listen...

300
00:48:49.660 --> 00:48:51.979
You know what...

301
00:48:56.220 --> 00:48:59.499
Let's see if we can find
something to eat.


302
00:49:01.780 --> 00:49:03.779
Reinhold.

303
00:49:05.580 --> 00:49:07.859
Come now.

304
00:49:43.860 --> 00:49:49.579
One of the girls at the boarding
house had her baby in Denmark.


305
00:49:49.780 --> 00:49:53.419
And she didn't have
to give the father's name.


306
00:50:06.820 --> 00:50:11.579
The baby can stay
with a foster mother in Denmark.


307
00:50:13.140 --> 00:50:17.099
Until your court case is over.
And I can go back to Vimmerby.


308
00:50:19.180 --> 00:50:22.899
Then you can get divorced
and we can be married.


309
00:50:24.900 --> 00:50:27.739
And then we'll bring the baby home.

310
00:51:18.060 --> 00:51:20.139
Passport, please.

311
00:51:21.780 --> 00:51:24.579
- I'm sorry?
- Your passport.


312
00:51:49.380 --> 00:51:52.059
Here we are.

313
00:52:06.500 --> 00:52:09.419
Mum! I'm here with Astrid Ericsson!

314
00:52:16.620 --> 00:52:20.659
- Marie.
- Astrid Ericsson, hello.


315
00:52:20.820 --> 00:52:23.819
Did you have a good trip?

316
00:52:24.020 --> 00:52:28.339
That's Esse, my other Swedish
foster child. Can you take him, Carl?


317
00:52:28.540 --> 00:52:30.579
(In Swedish)
You can hang your coat here.


318
00:52:32.820 --> 00:52:37.539
- So you speak Swedish?
- You're not my first Swedish girl.


319
00:52:39.060 --> 00:52:42.139
Let me show you where you're staying.

320
00:52:50.340 --> 00:52:53.619
Go ahead and lie down,
you must need a rest.


321
00:52:57.460 --> 00:52:59.819
Are your legs swollen?

322
00:53:03.660 --> 00:53:06.779
May I feel
if the baby has turned properly?


323
00:53:06.980 --> 00:53:09.419
Yes, go ahead.

324
00:53:18.900 --> 00:53:21.699
I'm just going to put my hand here.

325
00:53:26.740 --> 00:53:28.859
Here's the head...

326
00:53:32.060 --> 00:53:33.739
Here, feel it.

327
00:53:44.500 --> 00:53:47.099
That's a little knee.

328
00:53:47.220 --> 00:53:49.859
It's a lively little person.

329
00:53:58.060 --> 00:54:01.179
Breathe, breathe!

330
00:54:01.300 --> 00:54:04.219
Lie back and breathe.

331
00:54:06.780 --> 00:54:11.379
- I can't do it.
- Next time, hold your breath.


332
00:54:12.380 --> 00:54:15.899
Good job! Keep going!

333
00:54:16.060 --> 00:54:18.299
With all your strength.

334
00:54:19.740 --> 00:54:22.739
Hold your breath
and try again. Come on.


335
00:54:22.900 --> 00:54:26.059
I can see the head!
Another push now...


336
00:54:28.100 --> 00:54:30.259
Breathe, breathe!

337
00:54:30.420 --> 00:54:33.419
And take a break. Good work.

338
00:54:36.620 --> 00:54:40.059
Now sit up and breathe, and pant.

339
00:54:41.580 --> 00:54:45.419
It's coming now. It's coming.
Get ready to push.


340
00:54:45.660 --> 00:54:48.819
Hold your breath, come on.

341
00:54:49.860 --> 00:54:52.099
Breathe out, breathe out.

342
00:54:53.420 --> 00:54:56.059
That's it.

343
00:54:56.260 --> 00:54:59.699
- Here it comes.
- It's beautiful.


344
00:55:02.700 --> 00:55:05.059
It's a handsome boy.

345
00:55:41.340 --> 00:55:44.419
My little boy...

346
00:55:51.380 --> 00:55:53.859
Hello!

347
00:55:56.420 --> 00:55:59.099
Hello there, little one.

348
00:56:26.300 --> 00:56:28.819
Here...

349
00:56:29.020 --> 00:56:32.219
If you'll hold it down... There...

350
00:56:43.380 --> 00:56:48.059
Everyone will know something's wrong
if I don't come home for Christmas.


351
00:56:52.380 --> 00:56:56.499
Now it might hurt a lot
over the next week or so-


352
00:56:56.700 --> 00:57:01.579
- but don't expel the milk,
because then you'll keep producing more.


353
00:57:37.980 --> 00:57:41.979
I'll come for him
as soon as the court case is over.


354
00:57:42.140 --> 00:57:44.819
I'll come as soon as I can.

355
00:57:48.500 --> 00:57:51.339
Hurry, or you'll miss your train.

356
00:58:10.340 --> 00:58:13.499
You can do this.

357
00:58:13.700 --> 00:58:16.059
Go on.

358
00:58:57.700 --> 00:59:00.139
Lift up your arms.

359
00:59:49.220 --> 00:59:52.099
He was christened at the hospital.

360
00:59:54.100 --> 00:59:55.899
His name is Lars.

361
01:00:01.020 --> 01:00:04.739
I think I'll call him Lasse, though.

362
01:00:04.940 --> 01:00:08.739
I'll come and put the bandages back on
before we leave.


363
01:00:32.460 --> 01:00:38.379
"There were shepherds in the same
country, watching their flocks by night.


364
01:00:38.580 --> 01:00:41.699
"An angel of the Lord
appeared before them-


365
01:00:41.860 --> 01:00:45.739
"- and the glory of the Lord
shone round about them.


366
01:00:45.940 --> 01:00:48.899
"And they became very afraid.

367
01:00:49.060 --> 01:00:53.179
"And the angel said unto them:
Fear not-


368
01:00:53.340 --> 01:00:58.019
"- for behold, I bring you
good tidings of great joy.


369
01:00:58.220 --> 01:01:02.899
"For unto you was born this day
in the City of David, a Saviour...


370
01:01:03.060 --> 01:01:06.179
which is Christ the Lord. "

371
01:01:06.380 --> 01:01:10.699
"And this shall be a sign unto you:
Ye shall find the babe"...


372
01:01:10.860 --> 01:01:14.899
TOMORROW 10 O'CLOCK
